Graeci optionem Carthaginiensibus faciunt, uti vel illi, &c.] This is the right reading. I remember that a Mr. Collins, an English classi- cal scholar, was a long time impatient to be introduced to my learned friend, the late John Walker; and that on my introducing him, I told him that Mr. Collins and myself were very desirous of obtaining his sentiments on this place of Crispus. I told him that Ι thought the text was faulty, and that we should read, Carthaginiensibus, not Car- thaginiensium, with which emendation he seemed delighted. I now find this is the reading in the edition of Kritzius, whose note I shall take the trouble of transcribing: Optionem facere cum significat po- testatem optandi vel eligendi dare (vid. Gronov. ad Plaut. Casin. 11, 2, 16), non usus tantum, sed recta ratio postulat rem, quae eligenda conceditur, genetivo enunciari, personam dativo significari, tertio casu ex verbo, secundo ex nomine optionis apto. Quare omnia pervertunt, qui eodem casu, quo res designatur, simul declarari posse putant per- sonam, cui datur rei copia, quod pariter absurdum est et solaecum, ac si quis contendat spem facere alicujus ita dici posse, ut genetivo non res intelligatur, quae speranda ostenditur, sed persona, quae sperare ju— betur. He says, Gronov. ad Liv. 27, 8, 3, Carthayiniensium defendit, non rectia—C·
